''Sources: amorphous BN,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|doi =10.1016/0022-3093(95)00748-2|title =Properties of amorphous boron nitride thin films|year =1996|author =R. Zedlitz|journal =Journal of Non-Crystalline Solids|volume =198–200|pages =403}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|doi =10.1364/AO.32.000091|pmid =20802666|title =Thermal conductivities of thin, sputtered optical films|year =1993|author =C. H. Henager, Jr.|journal =Applied Optics|volume =32|issue =1|pages =91}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|doi =10.1016/S0925-9635(98)00394-X|title =Microstructure and mechanical properties of pulsed laser deposited boron nitride films|year =1999|author =S. Weissmantel|journal =Diamond and Related Materials|volume =8|pages =377|issue =2–5}}&lt;/ref&gt; crystalline BN,&lt;ref name=BN&gt;{{cite book| title = Landolt-Börnstein – Group VIII Advanced Materials and Technologies: Powder Metallurgy Data. Refractory, Hard and Intermetallic Materials| chapter = 13.5 Properties of diamond and cubic boron nitride|volume = 2A2| doi = 10.1007/b83029| isbn = 978-3-540-42961-6| pages = 118–139| author = ed.: P. Beiss ''et al.'', Authors: G. Leichtfried ''et al.''| year = 2002| publisher = Springer| location = Berlin}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=ioffe/&gt; graphite,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book| author = P. Delhaes| title = Graphite and Precursors| publisher = CRC Press| year =2001| isbn = 9056992287}}&lt;/ref&gt; diamond''.&lt;ref name=ioffe&gt;{{cite web| url= http://www.ioffe.ru/SVA/NSM/Semicond/BN/index.html| title=Ioffe database| accessdate=2009-05-05}}&lt;/ref&gt;
{{clear}}
The partly [[ionic bond|ionic]] structure of BN layers in h-BN reduces covalency and electrical conductivity, whereas the interlayer interaction increases resulting in higher hardness of h-BN relative to graphite. The reduced electron-delocalization in hexagonal-BN is also indicated by its absence of color and a large [[band gap]]. Very different bonding – strong covalent within the [[basal plane]]s (planes where boron and nitrogen atoms are covalently bonded) and weak between them – causes high [[anisotropy]] of most properties of h-BN.

For example, the hardness, electrical and thermal conductivity are much higher within the planes than perpendicular to them. On the contrary, the properties of c-BN and w-BN are more homogeneous. 

Those materials are extremely hard, with the hardness of c-BN being slightly smaller and w-BN even higher than that of diamond.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal| author =Z. Pan |title = Harder than Diamond: Superior Indentation Strength of Wurtzite BN and Lonsdaleite| journal=Physical Review Letters |volume = 102 |page = 055503 |year =2009 |doi =10.1103/PhysRevLett.102.055503| last2 =Sun| first2 =Hong| last3 =Zhang| first3 =Yi| last4 =Chen| first4 =Changfeng | pmid=19257519 | bibcode=2009PhRvL.102e5503P| issue =5}}&lt;/ref&gt; Because of much better stability to heat and metals, c-BN surpasses diamond in mechanical applications.&lt;ref name=dkg&gt;{{cite journal| title = Hexagonal Boron Nitride (hBN) – Applications from Metallurgy to Cosmetics| url = http://www.esk.com/uploads/tx_userjspresseveroeff/PR_0712_CFI_12-2007_Hexagonales-BN_e_01.pdf| author =M. Engler| journal = Cfi/Ber. DKG |volume = 84|year = 2007| page = D25| issn = 0173-9913}}&lt;/ref&gt; The thermal conductivity of BN is among the highest of all electric insulators (see table). 

Boron nitride can be doped p-type with Be and n-type with boron, sulfur, silicon or if co-doped with carbon and nitrogen.&lt;ref name=BN/&gt; Both hexagonal and cubic BN are wide-gap semiconductors with a band gap energy corresponding to the UV region. If voltage is applied to h-BN &lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |author = Y. Kubota|title = Deep Ultraviolet Light-Emitting Hexagonal Boron Nitride Synthesized at Atmospheric Pressure| doi = 10.1126/science.1144216 |journal = Science |pmid = 17702939 |volume = 317 |issue = 5840|year = 2007 |page = 932 |last2 = Watanabe |first2 = K. |last3 = Tsuda |first3 = O. |last4 = Taniguchi |first4 = T.}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;taniguchi&quot;&gt;{{cite journal| author = K. Watanabe, T. Taniguchi, H. Kanda |title = Direct-bandgap properties and evidence for ultraviolet lasing of hexagonal boron nitride single crystal| doi = 10.1038/nmat1134 |journal = Nature Materials| pmid = 15156198 |volume = 3| issue = 6 |year = 2004 |page = 404}}&lt;/ref&gt; or c-BN,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal| author =T. Taniguchi |title =Ultraviolet light emission from self-organized p–n domains in cubic boron nitride bulk single crystals grown under high pressure| doi = 10.1063/1.1524295 |journal = Appl. Phys. Lett.|volume = 81 |year =2002 |page = 4145| last2 =Watanabe| first2 =K.| last3 =Koizumi| first3 =S.| last4 =Sakaguchi| first4 =I.| last5 =Sekiguchi| first5 =T.| last6 =Yamaoka| first6 =S.| issue =22}}&lt;/ref&gt; then it emits UV light in the range 215–250&amp;nbsp;nm and therefore can potentially be used as [[light emitting diodes]] (LEDs) or lasers.

Little is known on melting behavior of boron nitride. It sublimates at 2973&amp;nbsp;°C at normal pressure releasing nitrogen gas and boron, but melts at elevated pressure.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|doi =10.1021/j100814a515|year =1962|author =Lloyd H. Dreger|journal =The Journal of Physical Chemistry|volume =66|pages =1556|last2 =Dadape|first2 =V. V.|last3 =Margrave|first3 =John L.|issue =8}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=wentorf/&gt;

===Thermal stability===
Hexagonal and cubic (and probably w-BN) BN show remarkable chemical and thermal stabilities. For example, h-BN is stable to decomposition in temperatures up to 1000&amp;nbsp;°C in air, 1400&amp;nbsp;°C in vacuum, and 2800&amp;nbsp;°C in an inert atmosphere. The reactivity of h-BN and c-BN is relatively similar, and the data for c-BN are summarized in the table below. 
